1
00:00:05,860 --> 00:00:08,083
Okay, I think I'm going to start.

2
00:00:10,566 --> 00:00:13,090
The first thing I'm just going to do is apologize for my voice.

3
00:00:13,250 --> 00:00:14,872
I'm sort of losing my voice at the moment,

4
00:00:14,952 --> 00:00:20,200
so if I become really quirky or just pass out, just carry on.

5
00:00:21,567 --> 00:00:24,369
Okay, so the subject of my talk is Glitter and Doom,

6
00:00:25,289 --> 00:00:27,191
production's role when making new things.

7
00:00:28,011 --> 00:00:32,014
So, making new things, it's a great thing.

8
00:00:33,355 --> 00:00:35,717
And I sometimes imagine that being a producer

9
00:00:36,337 --> 00:00:39,780
is something like being the ringmaster of a glittery circus.

10
00:00:40,360 --> 00:00:44,103
And every day the magic can happen, and glitter can rain from the skies,

11
00:00:44,683 --> 00:00:46,364
but then equally bad things can happen,

12
00:00:46,424 --> 00:00:50,427
and everyone can feel like they have just seen someone get eaten by the lion.

13
00:00:51,915 --> 00:00:56,763
Sometimes you need to fail spectacularly before going on to making something great.

14
00:00:57,223 --> 00:01:00,789
And for me it's the glitter and doom of the process that makes everything so magical.

15
00:01:05,216 --> 00:01:08,357
So my core skill is production.

16
00:01:09,177 --> 00:01:13,378
I'm now the studio director at Media Molecule, and I was sort of strong-armed into doing

17
00:01:13,398 --> 00:01:17,219
this talk at the advisory board meeting last year, and I've been trying to think for ages

18
00:01:17,299 --> 00:01:18,699
about what to talk about.

19
00:01:18,719 --> 00:01:23,960
It's kind of difficult to find an angle with production, because a lot of my approach is

20
00:01:24,020 --> 00:01:26,781
instinctual, and it's a big part of my personality.

21
00:01:27,541 --> 00:01:30,964
And I don't think that anyone should actually come and replicate any of my processes,

22
00:01:31,464 --> 00:01:33,986
because our setup is unique and it's imperfect.

23
00:01:34,787 --> 00:01:38,050
But I hope to offer some ideas and insights that are going to help you,

24
00:01:38,130 --> 00:01:39,451
or resonate with you in some way.

25
00:01:39,471 --> 00:01:42,293
So anyway, I started by thinking about producers,

26
00:01:42,313 --> 00:01:43,534
and these are all producers.

27
00:01:43,554 --> 00:01:46,416
They're actually all film and music producers.

28
00:01:47,197 --> 00:01:50,878
And I sort of started with looking for a quote.

29
00:01:51,378 --> 00:01:58,499
So this one, a producer is a vehicle to get the artist's creativity on the table in a way that is accessible to an audience.

30
00:01:59,160 --> 00:02:02,560
And this really chimed with me because it perfectly describes the role of a producer.

31
00:02:03,100 --> 00:02:06,601
And yet the quote is from Keith Olsen, who is a music producer,

32
00:02:06,641 --> 00:02:09,582
so it's describing the relationship between a band and a record producer.

33
00:02:10,705 --> 00:02:12,606
Obviously, all forms of entertainment,

34
00:02:12,766 --> 00:02:15,687
be it film, television, radio, theater, or games,

35
00:02:15,747 --> 00:02:16,507
have producers.

36
00:02:17,207 --> 00:02:19,388
But this is what they share in common with each other.

37
00:02:20,649 --> 00:02:22,890
Clearly, there are a lot of different tasks in the area

38
00:02:22,930 --> 00:02:24,410
between the idea and the audience,

39
00:02:24,991 --> 00:02:27,492
and so the roles are different within each area.

40
00:02:27,592 --> 00:02:31,053
But essentially, we're here to collaborate with the team

41
00:02:31,593 --> 00:02:33,474
and ship that thing and get it out to an audience,

42
00:02:33,554 --> 00:02:34,595
regardless of the industry.

43
00:02:35,656 --> 00:02:38,997
People within games, we chase the perfect process all the time.

44
00:02:39,017 --> 00:02:42,158
And games development, for me, by its very nature,

45
00:02:42,178 --> 00:02:45,719
the process won't actually ever probably settle down,

46
00:02:45,839 --> 00:02:46,959
or it certainly won't for a while.

47
00:02:47,799 --> 00:02:49,460
And there are some aspects that we should repeat

48
00:02:49,500 --> 00:02:51,941
and we should spend time resolving.

49
00:02:52,401 --> 00:02:54,241
But especially when you're making new things,

50
00:02:54,501 --> 00:02:56,462
you need to be able to be experimental.

51
00:02:57,963 --> 00:03:01,767
And when you're also dealing with new hardware platforms or technology, things can get really

52
00:03:01,787 --> 00:03:02,227
interesting.

53
00:03:02,788 --> 00:03:07,012
So we've got to allow for the fact that it won't always be a smooth ride, and making

54
00:03:07,072 --> 00:03:13,799
great stuff with an imperfect process is better than making terrible or mediocre things with

55
00:03:13,819 --> 00:03:14,800
a really great process.

56
00:03:15,781 --> 00:03:17,603
So to bring it back to the quote.

57
00:03:18,664 --> 00:03:21,726
Rather than worrying all the time about a process when you're making something new,

58
00:03:22,267 --> 00:03:26,871
you need to sort of focus as a producer how you're actually going to help your team get that artist creativity

59
00:03:27,311 --> 00:03:29,093
onto the table and then out to an audience.

60
00:03:29,853 --> 00:03:31,415
And thinking about my job in this way,

61
00:03:31,435 --> 00:03:35,458
I realized that we kind of have like a poor language of how we talk about games production.

62
00:03:36,059 --> 00:03:42,084
So I'm going to be drawing parallels between like mainly music and making games as a way to sort of

63
00:03:42,684 --> 00:03:43,445
describe my

64
00:03:44,866 --> 00:03:45,066
self.

65
00:03:46,453 --> 00:03:49,256
Okay, this next one is another one that really chimes with me.

66
00:03:49,376 --> 00:03:52,119
So, you put the cake dish over the bat phone

67
00:03:52,159 --> 00:03:53,661
and protects you from the outside world

68
00:03:53,801 --> 00:03:55,823
and helps you actualize the sounds that are in your head.

69
00:03:56,484 --> 00:04:00,328
It's another band's production producer quote.

70
00:04:01,131 --> 00:04:03,572
So brand new ideas are really fragile.

71
00:04:03,872 --> 00:04:05,953
And it's our job to protect these ideas.

72
00:04:06,593 --> 00:04:08,553
And I've always believed massively in shelter and

73
00:04:08,593 --> 00:04:11,974
protect, but I actually really like the visual of this one a

74
00:04:11,994 --> 00:04:13,675
lot more, so I'll probably say this from now on.

75
00:04:14,815 --> 00:04:17,516
So it's protecting the idea, and the team, and the studio

76
00:04:17,556 --> 00:04:18,337
from the outside world.

77
00:04:19,782 --> 00:04:22,525
This quote represents how I like to think about my job a lot.

78
00:04:22,965 --> 00:04:25,288
It isn't referencing the kind of nightmare scenario

79
00:04:25,348 --> 00:04:27,710
where a music producer has been hired by the record label

80
00:04:28,090 --> 00:04:30,573
to impose a sound on the band against their will.

81
00:04:31,433 --> 00:04:33,996
Clearly, the quote is referencing the kind of producer

82
00:04:34,016 --> 00:04:37,880
who wants to help an artist or a band nurture their concept

83
00:04:38,120 --> 00:04:39,221
and bring it to fruition,

84
00:04:39,882 --> 00:04:41,803
where there is mutual respect for each other

85
00:04:41,984 --> 00:04:43,405
and they have the backing and the blessing

86
00:04:43,425 --> 00:04:44,106
of their record label.

87
00:04:45,692 --> 00:04:48,133
And taking this to heart, sort of remember these guys

88
00:04:48,213 --> 00:04:50,194
and how obnoxiously brilliant they were when

89
00:04:50,214 --> 00:04:51,334
they were first on the scene.

90
00:04:51,995 --> 00:04:55,036
The Beastie Boys, I don't know who was listening to them

91
00:04:55,116 --> 00:04:57,537
right back then, but they were just so obnoxiously awful.

92
00:04:57,617 --> 00:04:58,318
But they were brilliant.

93
00:04:58,778 --> 00:04:59,798
They weren't calmed down.

94
00:04:59,878 --> 00:05:00,759
They weren't silenced.

95
00:05:00,799 --> 00:05:01,919
They weren't told to behave.

96
00:05:02,419 --> 00:05:04,460
And their record producers pushed them to be themselves

97
00:05:04,500 --> 00:05:05,621
and make them what they wanted to be.

98
00:05:05,661 --> 00:05:06,681
And I think it worked out OK.

99
00:05:08,226 --> 00:05:13,329
And when we talk about producers, it's me making a spreadsheet, being a producer,

100
00:05:13,569 --> 00:05:16,610
there is often this desire to sort of pigeonhole which type you are.

101
00:05:16,630 --> 00:05:21,193
Are you like a development manager? Are you a creative producer? Are you a producer-producer?

102
00:05:21,213 --> 00:05:24,115
And effectively people always want to split us between

103
00:05:24,155 --> 00:05:26,156
do you care about time or do you care about the product?

104
00:05:27,196 --> 00:05:32,457
And there's this real tension between creativity and delivery, and so if you work somewhere where there is that split,

105
00:05:32,497 --> 00:05:36,218
it can be really difficult to figure out where you sit or where your allegiances lie.

106
00:05:36,958 --> 00:05:39,779
And I am, like, I can only really describe myself as a producer.

107
00:05:39,999 --> 00:05:43,800
I'm a games producer, and I have a wide and varied set of skills

108
00:05:44,380 --> 00:05:48,981
that enable me to be able to think about what we make as a product, and I can schedule, and I can think about people.

109
00:05:49,938 --> 00:05:53,860
And it's a skilled job, not one just for people who aren't artists or audio or designers.

110
00:05:54,440 --> 00:05:58,102
And it can be a dumping ground for people who are passionate about games,

111
00:05:58,182 --> 00:06:02,205
but don't actually have one of the other skills and oftentimes don't actually have production skills either.

112
00:06:02,225 --> 00:06:06,587
And I think probably that's the role of production differs so much everywhere

113
00:06:06,667 --> 00:06:08,388
because the industry is growing so quickly.

114
00:06:09,109 --> 00:06:14,711
From the bedroom garage games to then making games with big teams and millions of, multi-millions

115
00:06:14,731 --> 00:06:16,452
of budget, it grew really fast.

116
00:06:16,572 --> 00:06:21,134
And so the role of producer came into existence before anyone had any time to work out what

117
00:06:21,154 --> 00:06:22,895
it was, and so we're still sort of figuring all that out.

118
00:06:23,495 --> 00:06:27,817
And so as production, we do have a duty to continue to evolve and iterate the role so

119
00:06:27,837 --> 00:06:29,938
that it works in the best way for our teams.

120
00:06:31,805 --> 00:06:35,006
So I'm kind of assuming that a lot of the room are producers.

121
00:06:35,367 --> 00:06:38,869
And a question that I'd sort of, focusing on us for a

122
00:06:38,909 --> 00:06:41,810
moment, I'd sort of ask you why and how you got into it.

123
00:06:41,830 --> 00:06:44,972
And for me, it sort of started when I was a really young girl.

124
00:06:45,012 --> 00:06:46,573
I've just always been really bossy.

125
00:06:47,153 --> 00:06:49,274
And I've always had a pretty clear idea of what I want out

126
00:06:49,334 --> 00:06:50,195
of the world.

127
00:06:51,475 --> 00:06:53,937
But it really started for me when I was between 14 and 17.

128
00:06:54,537 --> 00:06:55,698
And I was really into music.

129
00:06:55,838 --> 00:06:58,039
And I was pretty sure that it was music or film

130
00:06:58,059 --> 00:06:58,719
that I'd get into.

131
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:04,644
And I was really passionate about the Sydney music scene, and I made a fanzine, and I hung out with people that did that,

132
00:07:04,684 --> 00:07:10,468
and I worked in a record store, and after doing work experience there, and I was really driven about this.

133
00:07:10,508 --> 00:07:12,710
I was going to gigs and hanging around and all of that.

134
00:07:14,640 --> 00:07:20,764
And sort of at this time when I was sort of starting to kind of get into that more and think about putting on gigs and making records with friends,

135
00:07:21,244 --> 00:07:23,825
I then got into making short films and disappeared into that world.

136
00:07:24,386 --> 00:07:28,068
But it's been when looking back now that I see how important this period was for me.

137
00:07:29,188 --> 00:07:38,094
And I was so inspired by the music that I was into and the punk and indie scene of the 80s and 90s had this real sense of everybody just wanting to get on with stuff.

138
00:07:38,794 --> 00:07:41,936
and just do things and not be waiting for anything, and it was intoxicating.

139
00:07:42,376 --> 00:07:45,038
And it's funny for me to even think that it was a form of rebellion

140
00:07:45,078 --> 00:07:46,579
when it's helped me so much in my life.

141
00:07:48,600 --> 00:07:51,122
So, yeah, so I declined moving on to film school

142
00:07:51,142 --> 00:07:53,183
and I got a job within the web world

143
00:07:54,204 --> 00:07:55,825
because people there were really inspiring

144
00:07:55,865 --> 00:07:58,467
and they had a desire to sort of pioneer

145
00:07:58,507 --> 00:08:02,349
how people were using web technology whilst also creating beautiful things.

146
00:08:03,523 --> 00:08:06,544
And these influences of my youth preoccupied me recently

147
00:08:06,604 --> 00:08:08,745
when I was in a store watching people choose games.

148
00:08:09,445 --> 00:08:11,085
It was a really diverse group of people,

149
00:08:11,145 --> 00:08:13,086
and watching them made me ruminate on taste.

150
00:08:13,686 --> 00:08:14,886
Right there in front of me, people

151
00:08:14,906 --> 00:08:16,067
were developing their taste.

152
00:08:16,127 --> 00:08:17,207
And they could have been picking up

153
00:08:17,627 --> 00:08:21,388
the item that may have some really big impact on them.

154
00:08:21,968 --> 00:08:23,849
It could be the one that helps them play with their siblings

155
00:08:23,889 --> 00:08:26,149
in a new way, or help them with communication,

156
00:08:26,770 --> 00:08:28,810
or be the one where they build their first bit of content

157
00:08:28,850 --> 00:08:30,310
for a game and realize that they're

158
00:08:30,330 --> 00:08:31,471
a powerful, creative being.

159
00:08:32,292 --> 00:08:35,870
And I remember these feelings when I was a teenager and coming across things that had impact.

160
00:08:36,700 --> 00:08:39,501
I remember coming across the white girl fanzine and music movement

161
00:08:39,641 --> 00:08:42,582
and their take on modern feminism was my take.

162
00:08:43,042 --> 00:08:44,962
It had impact because they weren't bullshitting

163
00:08:45,002 --> 00:08:47,363
and they were so passionate about what they actually believed.

164
00:08:47,943 --> 00:08:51,365
And that work had impact and it inspired me.

165
00:08:51,385 --> 00:08:55,766
And all of my major influences are things that have personality and impact.

166
00:08:56,406 --> 00:09:00,208
I have a drive to work with people who have personality, uniqueness and a take

167
00:09:00,568 --> 00:09:01,948
and I'm afraid to put it together.

168
00:09:03,073 --> 00:09:05,658
Then I hope that in doing that we might make something special together.

169
00:09:05,698 --> 00:09:08,142
And I want to help them manifest that because that's what I'm good at.

170
00:09:08,683 --> 00:09:10,707
And then we can all see it and experience it together.

171
00:09:10,807 --> 00:09:12,170
And maybe it may inspire somebody.

172
00:09:12,310 --> 00:09:15,636
And these are the things that drive me as a producer and make me want to continue being one.

173
00:09:16,825 --> 00:09:19,929
So when I was around eight, when I finally got to England,

174
00:09:21,090 --> 00:09:24,474
I got a great job at Criterion.

175
00:09:24,614 --> 00:09:27,718
And it was really, I just got into games in a roundabout way.

176
00:09:28,078 --> 00:09:30,040
But the love affair sort of started at that same time,

177
00:09:30,060 --> 00:09:32,783
when I realized that the people in games are actually amazing.

178
00:09:33,584 --> 00:09:35,145
I was really lucky to find the right team.

179
00:09:35,306 --> 00:09:37,588
And in your early career, and if you're in your early career,

180
00:09:37,628 --> 00:09:40,310
it's really important to find a great studio

181
00:09:40,430 --> 00:09:41,591
and someone that you can learn from.

182
00:09:41,651 --> 00:09:43,372
And I had a great mentor in Fiona Sperry.

183
00:09:44,513 --> 00:09:46,995
And the way that she taught me, the way that I worked with her,

184
00:09:47,095 --> 00:09:48,837
sort of informs how I work now.

185
00:09:49,557 --> 00:09:53,280
Making Burnout year upon year taught us the craft of making games.

186
00:09:54,141 --> 00:09:59,724
I spent the best part of my 20s sort of hunched over a desk playing games and assigning bugs and writing lots of post-it notes.

187
00:10:01,424 --> 00:10:02,745
So I definitely know how to make a game.

188
00:10:03,125 --> 00:10:06,267
And there came a point where my career, I could, big things could become more personal.

189
00:10:06,907 --> 00:10:10,389
And I didn't have a, I didn't drive while I made Burnout. I didn't have a car,

190
00:10:10,469 --> 00:10:12,430
so it's a bit hard to understand it all the time.

191
00:10:14,185 --> 00:10:17,667
But I wanted to sort of play around with the skills that I'd learned at Criterion.

192
00:10:18,227 --> 00:10:23,570
So Christmas 2005 at my house, this is the invitation I found this morning, Alex and

193
00:10:23,590 --> 00:10:27,052
Mark sort of told me about the plans that they had and the rest was history.

194
00:10:28,232 --> 00:10:33,575
So I started at Molecule in 2006 and since the start we've had this mission at Media

195
00:10:33,595 --> 00:10:36,616
Molecule to make innovative games within the genre we call creative gaming.

196
00:10:37,477 --> 00:10:40,359
I'm a believer in that we should make things that touch people.

197
00:10:40,379 --> 00:10:44,842
A media molecule is, the mission is really personal to us

198
00:10:44,862 --> 00:10:46,963
because it's a mission that's filled with people who are makers.

199
00:10:47,564 --> 00:10:51,366
I didn't come from a focus test or even figuring this out up front.

200
00:10:51,866 --> 00:10:53,567
There are individual and personal stories

201
00:10:53,587 --> 00:10:55,288
that are background to building these projects.

202
00:10:55,849 --> 00:10:58,190
Little Big Planet's game making genesis

203
00:10:58,330 --> 00:11:00,972
goes back to our creative director Mark Healey's Commodore 64 days as a child.

204
00:11:03,714 --> 00:11:07,777
His bedroom hobby has led to him having a 20-year-plus successful career within games.

205
00:11:08,458 --> 00:11:12,061
And from him, the idea of making a creative tool that could give people this experience

206
00:11:12,101 --> 00:11:15,884
was something that was really personal to him, and he was really passionate about it,

207
00:11:15,924 --> 00:11:18,746
and he was unwavering in his conviction that people would actually be there.

208
00:11:20,280 --> 00:11:24,122
And that's sort of why we, oh no, hang on.

209
00:11:24,142 --> 00:11:26,404
Yes, so many people's creativity has been sort of fed

210
00:11:26,484 --> 00:11:28,065
by things like that within the molecule,

211
00:11:28,105 --> 00:11:29,206
Tony Hart or Lego.

212
00:11:29,606 --> 00:11:32,568
And so their personal mission has been to share the joy

213
00:11:32,608 --> 00:11:34,069
they got out of these things as young people

214
00:11:34,089 --> 00:11:35,430
and inspire other young people.

215
00:11:36,151 --> 00:11:38,012
And so that's sort of why we all make things, isn't it?

216
00:11:38,072 --> 00:11:39,933
It's a way of us expressing something.

217
00:11:40,434 --> 00:11:42,175
And as makers, we've all been inspired

218
00:11:42,215 --> 00:11:43,856
and we seek out inspiration,

219
00:11:43,896 --> 00:11:47,118
which then helps us actually make more.

220
00:11:47,179 --> 00:11:49,400
And this is great cycle that we're sort of continuing.

221
00:11:50,529 --> 00:11:53,732
So we make special stuff when it comes from a personal place.

222
00:11:54,332 --> 00:11:56,874
And creating from this place may not dictate how successful

223
00:11:56,934 --> 00:11:58,996
it is, but it will certainly mean that you have a strong

224
00:11:59,036 --> 00:12:02,118
chance of creating something that is unique and has impact.

225
00:12:04,199 --> 00:12:06,681
So to arrive at these transcendental places as a

226
00:12:06,741 --> 00:12:10,304
team, which is obviously the Holy Grail, what you need is

227
00:12:10,344 --> 00:12:12,706
to gather this group of people together who are going to jam

228
00:12:12,746 --> 00:12:15,688
and collaborate really well, and who are going to get off

229
00:12:15,748 --> 00:12:18,190
on each other's ideas, and who will be inspired by each other

230
00:12:18,370 --> 00:12:18,790
to be better.

231
00:12:19,651 --> 00:12:24,197
It's immensely important that there is a crossover of taste and interest and skill and respect.

232
00:12:25,178 --> 00:12:27,941
When we hire people, part of the interview is sort of this fitting in bit,

233
00:12:28,041 --> 00:12:31,926
and what that really means is, is there enough of a taste crossover?

234
00:12:31,946 --> 00:12:36,972
And do we have the same view of what's good, and how will they behave when the crap hits the fan?

235
00:12:38,140 --> 00:12:41,081
