559
00:30:51,852 --> 00:30:52,973
and they will need their courage,

560
00:30:53,393 --> 00:30:56,595
the same rock and roll attitude that causes a band to get up on stage

561
00:30:56,655 --> 00:30:59,117
and confidently present themselves and their message to the world.

562
00:30:59,798 --> 00:31:02,760
Production's role at this stage is to facilitate this sort of course correction.

563
00:31:03,280 --> 00:31:06,643
When a project is lost, your creative directors are the bright shining lights,

564
00:31:07,243 --> 00:31:08,264
your first port of call.

565
00:31:08,444 --> 00:31:09,285
And when they are lost,

566
00:31:09,785 --> 00:31:12,047
you just need to really help them trace back to the beginning.

567
00:31:12,607 --> 00:31:14,349
Why have they made this project in the first place?

568
00:31:14,469 --> 00:31:15,810
And help them build it back up from there.

569
00:31:16,699 --> 00:31:19,880
People will rely on you to find ways to start conversations

570
00:31:19,980 --> 00:31:21,721
and to talk actually about what's happening

571
00:31:22,121 --> 00:31:24,502
and what people think needs to happen to improve the situation.

572
00:31:24,982 --> 00:31:26,583
You need to help people be able to zoom out

573
00:31:26,623 --> 00:31:27,884
and look at the big picture of things.

574
00:31:28,764 --> 00:31:30,945
A truly great producer can draw a team together

575
00:31:31,085 --> 00:31:32,686
when they need to,

576
00:31:32,806 --> 00:31:34,706
and leaves them to it when they need to.

577
00:31:35,127 --> 00:31:36,827
They can raise it to DEF CON level,

578
00:31:36,887 --> 00:31:37,948
all-out nuclear panic,

579
00:31:38,348 --> 00:31:39,869
three weeks before anyone has noticed,

580
00:31:39,909 --> 00:31:40,689
including the publisher.

581
00:31:42,032 --> 00:31:46,395
My point there is that a great producer takes a team to levels it could never have reached otherwise,

582
00:31:46,735 --> 00:31:52,479
and isn't afraid to make the hard decisions. It's an immensely creative and instinctive process as well as being very hard work.

583
00:31:53,619 --> 00:31:55,821
So you need to ask yourselves of your team,

584
00:31:55,861 --> 00:32:02,064
do they trust you to know exactly what risks to take and which ones to leave on the table or vice versa?

585
00:32:02,765 --> 00:32:06,467
And do they trust you to be able to see the big picture when they can't?

586
00:32:09,312 --> 00:32:13,775
So what was really needed to sort of turn Tearaway into a project firing on all cylinders

587
00:32:13,795 --> 00:32:18,099
was getting the team to work really well together and then to sort of continue moving on with

588
00:32:18,159 --> 00:32:18,639
momentum.

589
00:32:18,699 --> 00:32:22,522
And so there was this moment many years ago when I was working on Burnout Revenge, which

590
00:32:22,562 --> 00:32:26,665
was sort of a particularly grueling project, where I stood on a table at our local pub

591
00:32:26,725 --> 00:32:30,527
and I mapped out our path to finaling using Lord of the Rings and Sauron and our quest

592
00:32:30,547 --> 00:32:32,369
to get to Mount Doom is my metaphor.

593
00:32:33,129 --> 00:32:35,211
It was very memorable because I was very passionate

594
00:32:35,751 --> 00:32:37,372
and we were very bonded in our challenge.

595
00:32:37,492 --> 00:32:40,674
And I'm reminded by one of my workmates all the time.

596
00:32:41,094 --> 00:32:43,436
And it makes me smile because I really recall the emotion

597
00:32:43,476 --> 00:32:45,017
that I felt about getting to the end.

598
00:32:45,798 --> 00:32:48,479
And as a producer, you sort of have to be that sort of crazy one

599
00:32:48,559 --> 00:32:50,921
who's ready to, who's leading the charge to the end

600
00:32:50,961 --> 00:32:52,622
with such vigor that you're unstoppable.

601
00:32:53,363 --> 00:32:55,744
And if you don't set that beat, then somebody else might,

602
00:32:55,924 --> 00:32:57,966
but chances are they won't because they've probably got

603
00:32:57,986 --> 00:32:59,927
a whole lot of other things on their mind and it's your job.

604
00:33:01,603 --> 00:33:04,204
We all sort of know that moment of reaching the end

605
00:33:04,864 --> 00:33:09,566
where you've actually created the amazing thing that you're proud of and has the personality that you've really worked hard for

606
00:33:09,586 --> 00:33:15,569
and is ready to be shared with the world and it's an incredible feeling and the team really rely on us being the ones to help them get there.

607
00:33:16,269 --> 00:33:20,554
So at the start, my focus is very much trying to figure out what's going on in our creative

608
00:33:20,574 --> 00:33:26,662
lead's heads and help the fragile thoughts knit together into something more.

609
00:33:26,742 --> 00:33:30,587
And then there's this moment which I've labelled as the eclipse, which is basically the moment

610
00:33:30,627 --> 00:33:35,312
where the idea is no longer fragile and it's known enough by the team for it to lead the

611
00:33:35,352 --> 00:33:35,553
team.

612
00:33:36,394 --> 00:33:39,857
And then once that sort of moment has happened, I sort of turn a bit more into a fan

613
00:33:39,877 --> 00:33:45,762
and sort of reviewing it as a finished thing and making sure we always have something amazing.

614
00:33:46,222 --> 00:33:48,504
The equivalent of sort of redoing every sort of take.

615
00:33:48,544 --> 00:33:52,408
And anyone who's been through filing with me will know that we spend a lot of time

616
00:33:52,428 --> 00:33:55,691
sort of reviewing and perfecting and challenging ourselves to make sure that we're finishing.

617
00:33:56,719 --> 00:34:00,361
So some of the most important work I do day to day is a simple act of just making sure

618
00:34:00,401 --> 00:34:01,142
that things happen.

619
00:34:01,642 --> 00:34:05,024
When I know the areas aren't consistent or up to scratch, I just organise reviews or

620
00:34:05,064 --> 00:34:07,206
I make people speak together when I know that they need to.

621
00:34:07,226 --> 00:34:11,308
I hold people accountable and I have really high expectations and people know that.

622
00:34:11,849 --> 00:34:15,591
I don't really care about being bad cop because my focus is to make sure that all of that

623
00:34:15,611 --> 00:34:19,714
sole tax that people are paying and this initial pain that we've gone through actually manifests

624
00:34:19,754 --> 00:34:20,835
into something that we're proud of.

625
00:34:21,623 --> 00:34:25,026
And we as producers, we really fail if the game doesn't live up to that potential.

626
00:34:25,547 --> 00:34:29,911
And no amount of post-mortems or even sort of fairly okay scores will change that,

627
00:34:29,931 --> 00:34:31,133
because once it's done, it's done.

628
00:34:33,876 --> 00:34:40,923
Okay, right, sorry, my slide seems to have stopped moving.

629
00:34:41,223 --> 00:34:43,145
So, five rules to make it happen.

630
00:34:44,307 --> 00:34:46,928
You've got to know the vision and know what the big picture is

631
00:34:46,948 --> 00:34:49,688
and sort of understand not just like what it is in writing,

632
00:34:49,768 --> 00:34:52,269
but actually why they want to make it in the first place.

633
00:34:52,349 --> 00:34:54,809
It's always really important to sort of have some idea

634
00:34:54,849 --> 00:34:56,469
of personally why it's important to them.

635
00:34:57,490 --> 00:35:00,110
And it sort of can't be your big picture or your vision.

636
00:35:00,170 --> 00:35:01,550
It has to be your creative leads.

637
00:35:02,671 --> 00:35:03,891
You need to know what is happening.

638
00:35:04,071 --> 00:35:06,311
And that means you need to sort of speak to people honestly

639
00:35:06,431 --> 00:35:08,312
and be speaking to them all the time on the team

640
00:35:08,332 --> 00:35:10,152
and kind of really having a gauge of what's going on.

641
00:35:11,299 --> 00:35:14,840
A simple exercise for you to do if you need one is, and I'm sure everyone already does this,

642
00:35:14,920 --> 00:35:18,562
but just something that I find really useful and do all the time is just write down everybody's names

643
00:35:19,162 --> 00:35:23,843
and then just ponder on them and think about them, what they're doing, what they need,

644
00:35:23,984 --> 00:35:27,045
what I feel like I need to communicate to them, or I think they need to communicate to me.

645
00:35:28,209 --> 00:35:30,151
And then workflow is obviously really important.

646
00:35:30,191 --> 00:35:31,432
It's kind of the unglamorous thing.

647
00:35:31,513 --> 00:35:34,256
But basically, do you actually know how hard it is to commit

648
00:35:34,276 --> 00:35:35,137
something into the game?

649
00:35:35,197 --> 00:35:36,138
Is it really difficult?

650
00:35:36,178 --> 00:35:39,062
Like, how much faff is there in between having a thought and

651
00:35:39,102 --> 00:35:40,303
actually it appearing on screen?

652
00:35:40,363 --> 00:35:41,545
It's really important that we put effort

653
00:35:41,585 --> 00:35:42,326
into making that good.

654
00:35:43,967 --> 00:35:44,527
Play the game.

655
00:35:44,787 --> 00:35:47,889
You need to be playing the game like an editor would read

656
00:35:47,909 --> 00:35:50,010
a book draft, or a music producer would listen to a

657
00:35:50,050 --> 00:35:52,051
song, or a film crew would watch rushes.

658
00:35:52,912 --> 00:35:54,933
And it's the only way to actually know if things are

659
00:35:54,973 --> 00:35:57,875
coming together, and particularly when we're making

660
00:35:57,915 --> 00:36:00,276
something new, because it's forming right in front of you.

661
00:36:00,356 --> 00:36:02,998
And sometimes things that you think are important aren't

662
00:36:03,018 --> 00:36:05,159
things that you felt would stand out.

663
00:36:05,840 --> 00:36:07,681
And it's the only way for you to be able to really tell

664
00:36:07,721 --> 00:36:11,443
whether or not, how important it is to organize a review to

665
00:36:11,463 --> 00:36:12,344
get something signed off.

666
00:36:13,553 --> 00:36:19,614
And if we can't get it to feel good now, then I ask you to think about what you're imagining is actually going to be done in the

667
00:36:19,654 --> 00:36:23,475
finaling phase to make it good and just get that done now instead.

668
00:36:24,615 --> 00:36:30,537
It's your job to sort of make that happen and people rely on that to happen, otherwise you can end up with that soup.

669
00:36:30,577 --> 00:36:31,697
Make sure you're team player too.

670
00:36:31,737 --> 00:36:35,678
That's the other obviously a really important thing and make sure people are thinking about what the end product needs to be.

671
00:36:37,158 --> 00:36:40,160
Because when you're finaling, you won't suddenly be able to rewrite lots of things.

672
00:36:40,540 --> 00:36:42,602
And once the game is shipped, you can't really change things.

673
00:36:42,622 --> 00:36:47,204
So this means everything that you do every day has got to be working towards that goal.

674
00:36:47,725 --> 00:36:49,286
And the only way to judge it is by playing the game.

675
00:36:51,767 --> 00:36:54,669
Yes, so don't wait. Oh, no, this picture's gone.

676
00:36:54,729 --> 00:36:56,590
There was a picture there, but it's gone. It doesn't matter.

677
00:36:57,974 --> 00:37:02,539
So find a way to plan that works for your team.

678
00:37:03,040 --> 00:37:04,982
And for us, we have a mentality of jamming.

679
00:37:05,503 --> 00:37:06,885
And I don't mean like game jams.

680
00:37:06,925 --> 00:37:09,027
I just mean a way of collaboration and working together.

681
00:37:09,508 --> 00:37:11,811
It's more like the idea of a band riffing together

682
00:37:11,831 --> 00:37:14,795
than just focused game jams.

683
00:37:15,604 --> 00:37:18,946
And this sort of makes me think about the Rolling Stones, and they formed in 1962.

684
00:37:19,526 --> 00:37:23,348
And whilst most of the band has changed, and their producers certainly have,

685
00:37:23,908 --> 00:37:27,390
despite some gaps they've stuck together, and sort of 50 years later this group

686
00:37:27,871 --> 00:37:30,692
sort of is bound together by music, and they've survived large,

687
00:37:30,972 --> 00:37:32,593
like very large amounts of dysfunction.

688
00:37:33,494 --> 00:37:37,155
I suspect that that's due to a large amount of respect for each other,

689
00:37:37,596 --> 00:37:40,117
and knowing that they're better off together than apart,

690
00:37:40,157 --> 00:37:42,578
and also the commercial success that they've experienced, obviously.

691
00:37:43,239 --> 00:37:46,120
The early chemistry was there between them very early on,

692
00:37:46,140 --> 00:37:47,941
and enough to get them together in the first place.

