00:38:58,510 --> 00:39:01,012
This is Mark and Kareem, if anyone doesn't recognise them.

714
00:39:01,072 --> 00:39:05,835
As producers, our nurturing side can often mean that we want to be able to protect people

715
00:39:05,875 --> 00:39:07,256
from experiencing creative pain.

716
00:39:08,316 --> 00:39:12,439
But sometimes it is kind of inevitable, and we need to make sure that there isn't a personal

717
00:39:12,459 --> 00:39:16,181
attack between people, and that people are supported.

718
00:39:16,221 --> 00:39:19,062
But the flip side of chemistry can be to have a certain amount of tension.

719
00:39:20,449 --> 00:39:22,870
So every day isn't going to be bliss or harmonious working,

720
00:39:22,890 --> 00:39:25,070
but the key is obviously to make sure that your team are respectful

721
00:39:25,110 --> 00:39:27,731
and people need to acknowledge if things go over the mark.

722
00:39:28,592 --> 00:39:32,633
Some of the world's most incredible partnerships have been fed by healthy doses of creative tension.

723
00:39:33,294 --> 00:39:36,055
And so it's important we don't just sort of always try to put out those fires

724
00:39:36,135 --> 00:39:38,235
and try and make everything okay all the time,

725
00:39:38,275 --> 00:39:41,357
because sometimes you just need to have a bit of that.

726
00:39:41,417 --> 00:39:44,658
So 25 sort of left-right brain people getting together to experiment

727
00:39:45,218 --> 00:39:48,219
and arrive at a commercial product that they're all proud of and have come up from scratch.

728
00:39:48,339 --> 00:39:49,340
It's like what could go wrong?

729
00:39:50,537 --> 00:39:54,764
So I like to embrace the chaos that Innova creates, and it's a big contributor to the

730
00:39:54,804 --> 00:39:57,129
feelings of glitter and doom that I sort of like.

731
00:39:58,995 --> 00:40:04,536
So communication is just as important externally as it is internally. I'm making a little bit planet now on tear away both

732
00:40:05,856 --> 00:40:09,557
Of our role was to continuously educate people on what we're doing

733
00:40:09,617 --> 00:40:14,378
And so they have the best information like when you're making a new project like you've moving at such a rate of knots

734
00:40:14,998 --> 00:40:20,099
That it's very difficult for people external to sort of keep up with you and to kind of then stay with you when you're talking

735
00:40:20,139 --> 00:40:21,900
about marketing plans and PR plans

736
00:40:22,900 --> 00:40:28,061
And it's sort of important and so we've sort of started which means sort of all these fairly lo-fi things

737
00:40:29,949 --> 00:40:31,931
This one has got kind of weird sound.

738
00:40:31,951 --> 00:40:35,456
But we've just started making these very lo-fi videos

739
00:40:35,516 --> 00:40:37,418
where we just talk through our milestones

740
00:40:37,478 --> 00:40:38,299
and send them over.

741
00:40:38,320 --> 00:40:43,206
And we're finding that that works really well for us.

742
00:40:44,447 --> 00:40:46,410
Oops.

743
00:40:48,407 --> 00:40:52,511
So the other part of that is to making sure that you protect

744
00:40:52,531 --> 00:40:54,593
your team from having to worry about things that they don't

745
00:40:54,613 --> 00:40:55,313
need to worry about.

746
00:40:55,814 --> 00:40:59,997
And sometimes there are people who have conversations which

747
00:41:00,477 --> 00:41:02,339
might force people into thinking that we need to

748
00:41:02,379 --> 00:41:03,360
pander to an audience.

749
00:41:04,181 --> 00:41:09,105
And if you're like us, with a lot of the team, there's parts

750
00:41:09,125 --> 00:41:10,966
of the business that they need to be exposed to and parts

751
00:41:10,986 --> 00:41:11,467
that they don't.

752
00:41:12,393 --> 00:41:17,014
And so, you know, sometimes people make us a bit afraid of our audiences,

753
00:41:17,054 --> 00:41:18,495
but I don't really think that we should be.

754
00:41:18,795 --> 00:41:21,176
When you're making something new, you sort of just have to focus

755
00:41:21,896 --> 00:41:25,277
on sort of being able to kind of get that thing out.

756
00:41:25,317 --> 00:41:27,418
And it can be tempting at the last moments of a project

757
00:41:27,878 --> 00:41:31,039
to want to finish it so much that you lose your mouse.

758
00:41:31,379 --> 00:41:31,640
Sorry.

759
00:41:32,440 --> 00:41:38,682
It can be tempting at the last moment of a project to want to finish so much that you can renege on really important things or get scared of how far you're taking it.

760
00:41:39,303 --> 00:41:45,265
And to think perhaps that you've all gone mad, but it's in these cases that you maybe just have a few trusted sources that can play the game for you.

761
00:41:45,925 --> 00:41:51,106
But there are always going to be people taking risks and there are always going to be people thinking about specific audiences.

762
00:41:51,967 --> 00:41:53,888
But it's those that do take risks, I think,

763
00:41:54,128 --> 00:41:55,549
at the projects and make an impression.

764
00:41:55,589 --> 00:41:58,490
And so to keep sort of the whole circle of creative life going,

765
00:41:58,510 --> 00:41:59,271
we all have to do that.

766
00:41:59,771 --> 00:42:01,812
And so as a production, we have to be the guardian

767
00:42:01,832 --> 00:42:03,213
of this battle, sort of to keep the faith.

768
00:42:03,933 --> 00:42:05,534
And we always have to back talented people,

769
00:42:05,574 --> 00:42:07,295
and we have to let their personalities shine

770
00:42:07,315 --> 00:42:07,976
through in their work.

771
00:42:08,396 --> 00:42:10,037
And we should back them when they need our support,

772
00:42:10,077 --> 00:42:11,878
and then we need to make sure that the team collaborates.

773
00:42:11,898 --> 00:42:13,219
And at any time people lose faith,

774
00:42:13,699 --> 00:42:15,720
we need to cheerlead them and avoid the compromises

775
00:42:15,740 --> 00:42:16,440
in the last minute.

776
00:42:17,061 --> 00:42:18,542
We sort of just need to make great stuff,

777
00:42:18,602 --> 00:42:19,522
and then the rest will follow.

778
00:42:23,023 --> 00:42:26,205
So some of you in the room probably won't be working for publishers anymore, and some

779
00:42:26,245 --> 00:42:26,705
of you will.

780
00:42:26,745 --> 00:42:30,147
And the way that I've always worked with publishers is a fair amount of transparency,

781
00:42:30,187 --> 00:42:33,689
and there's never been a point in pretending that you're somewhere that you're not,

782
00:42:33,729 --> 00:42:35,371
as they can largely see through that anyway.

783
00:42:36,151 --> 00:42:38,813
The thing that they're most interested in always is sort of what your plan is.

784
00:42:39,273 --> 00:42:42,735
And if you're in a crisis, it's always sort of good to be honest, as long as, you know,

785
00:42:43,296 --> 00:42:44,396
they will have seen that before.

786
00:42:46,057 --> 00:42:48,879
The thing that they're just going to be wanting to know is that you know what you're actually

787
00:42:48,899 --> 00:42:50,961
doing about it and how you're sort of going to get back on course.

788
00:42:51,561 --> 00:42:53,462
We've been incredibly lucky working with Sony.

789
00:42:53,602 --> 00:42:56,783
We were small and they've sort of never really interfered with what we do creatively.

790
00:42:57,443 --> 00:43:01,004
And thankfully for us, that's sort of set a precedent for how we've worked with them the whole way along.

791
00:43:01,544 --> 00:43:04,505
We have a really strong relationship with all of the producers that we work with there

792
00:43:04,525 --> 00:43:07,306
and there's a mutual respect, even if we don't agree all the time.

793
00:43:08,126 --> 00:43:11,227
And as a producer, it may be your role to sustain these relationships.

794
00:43:11,287 --> 00:43:15,808
And you need to know when you need to use the cake dish and put it over the phone.

795
00:43:15,868 --> 00:43:19,529
And you need to know when you have to open the doors and let people in to see what's actually going on.

796
00:43:20,209 --> 00:43:23,870
Someone had said to me a little while ago that I have a reputation for giving a good no.

797
00:43:24,770 --> 00:43:29,311
And I'm not really sure what that means other than I behave as a bouncer for Media Molecule,

798
00:43:29,331 --> 00:43:31,992
much as annoyance to people who want things from us.

799
00:43:32,592 --> 00:43:35,113
And sometimes that cake dish comes in very handy for me.

800
00:43:36,574 --> 00:43:41,437
The most important thing with making new things is that it's very challenging, but it's a lot of fun.

801
00:43:41,957 --> 00:43:45,238
If you have the team and you believe in their vision and you can actually do your job,

802
00:43:45,319 --> 00:43:48,680
then you should be on course to be able to do something, so you just need to not be afraid.

803
00:43:49,879 --> 00:43:52,602
When we were making LittleBigPlanet, we really had no idea what we were doing,

804
00:43:52,882 --> 00:43:55,625
and with regard to the logistics of the UGC service,

805
00:43:56,146 --> 00:43:57,427
we all learned that the hard way.

806
00:43:57,447 --> 00:44:01,591
And we didn't really know if anyone would create anything until the beta trials,

807
00:44:01,711 --> 00:44:04,534
which were a beta, which was probably too late to figure out anyway.

808
00:44:05,015 --> 00:44:08,698
But when we started to see those level numbers draw up, we were just so happy.

809
00:44:09,419 --> 00:44:13,702
We had this belief though in a united desire to jump into the unknown and give it a go

810
00:44:13,822 --> 00:44:14,883
and to figure it out as we went.

811
00:44:15,364 --> 00:44:19,226
And we lived in this world for six years and then decided that it was time to jump into

812
00:44:19,246 --> 00:44:22,309
another unknown with two new peers and it's been so hard.

813
00:44:22,969 --> 00:44:26,472
And the last years have seen many of us really overstretched and things taking longer than

814
00:44:26,512 --> 00:44:29,594
they should and many of our internal processes broken down.

815
00:44:30,375 --> 00:44:32,176
And it's been really hard, and we've got so much wrong.

816
00:44:32,216 --> 00:44:33,678
But I feel like, within production,

817
00:44:33,698 --> 00:44:35,999
we've been steering these icebergs.

818
00:44:36,620 --> 00:44:38,522
But despite the mistakes that we've made,

819
00:44:38,682 --> 00:44:41,484
we've all learned lessons about the games we're making

820
00:44:42,065 --> 00:44:42,965
and the people that we are.

821
00:44:43,005 --> 00:44:46,008
And I think we're making games that only we would make,

822
00:44:46,128 --> 00:44:47,509
and there's something special about that.

823
00:44:48,190 --> 00:44:50,332
I've had so many joyous moments, and I'm

824
00:44:50,372 --> 00:44:52,253
so happy to see the world of Tearaway come to life

825
00:44:52,293 --> 00:44:54,095
and the team overcome the challenges that they've had.

826
00:44:54,535 --> 00:44:56,717
And it's exciting to see everyone knuckle down

827
00:44:56,857 --> 00:44:57,638
for the final stretch.

828
00:44:58,866 --> 00:45:03,850
LBP and now Tearaway, our other project, will stretch us and the other one we announced, well we sort of showed some stuff off,

829
00:45:04,370 --> 00:45:09,915
they will stretch us, but that's because we're sort of reaching for something and we're taking creative risks and we're taking studio risks

830
00:45:09,975 --> 00:45:11,396
and we're generally not staying still.

831
00:45:12,417 --> 00:45:17,221
But that does mean we can get to somewhere special and we're going to be telling a personal story and

832
00:45:17,261 --> 00:45:22,165
making, you know, making something close to us means that we can sort of deliver experiences that are really unique for our audiences.

833
00:45:24,085 --> 00:45:25,665
So yeah, so just coming back to these,

834
00:45:25,685 --> 00:45:28,366
I think these are, I'll probably write these on post-it notes

835
00:45:28,386 --> 00:45:29,606
and put them on my desk as well.

836
00:45:30,947 --> 00:45:32,507
So yes, these are two things to remember.

837
00:45:33,687 --> 00:45:35,568
So yes, glitter and doom.

838
00:45:36,828 --> 00:45:39,409
Making new things means that you have to be a good producer,

839
00:45:39,529 --> 00:45:41,270
probably a really good producer,

840
00:45:41,890 --> 00:45:43,030
and we also just struggle with that,

841
00:45:43,050 --> 00:45:44,411
having to learn like every day

842
00:45:44,491 --> 00:45:46,311
and have days where I feel like I'm good

843
00:45:46,331 --> 00:45:47,972
and days where I feel like I'm really crap.

844
00:45:48,918 --> 00:45:52,880
But you just need to work hard, and you actually need to just love the glitter and doom of development.

845
00:45:53,540 --> 00:45:57,882
So my core to action with any producers is that you will have joined the industry for a reason,

846
00:45:57,922 --> 00:46:02,844
and you've probably got a whole bankload of interests and passions and things that you're into.

847
00:46:03,584 --> 00:46:07,926
And you probably may have been knocked back at some point and told that production is unimportant,

848
00:46:08,086 --> 00:46:12,328
or you're not part of the team, or you're not creative, or you don't matter, or number crunches and all that stuff.

849
00:46:13,068 --> 00:46:14,929
But I just don't think we should work with people like that.

850
00:46:16,367 --> 00:46:18,709
I know that I can add things and I'm really confident about that.

851
00:46:19,350 --> 00:46:25,537
I think the way that we need to think about it is that we can be critical to making a

852
00:46:25,558 --> 00:46:32,065
game successful and we can be critical to helping teams birth new ideas and be a part

853
00:46:32,085 --> 00:46:33,026
of that process.

854
00:46:33,186 --> 00:46:34,808
You really can pull your team towards that.

855
00:46:35,429 --> 00:46:37,230
So even when you're just tracking something,

856
00:46:37,270 --> 00:46:39,870
you need to be focused on the project being the best

857
00:46:39,890 --> 00:46:40,530
that it can be.

858
00:46:40,550 --> 00:46:42,511
The industry right now isn't going

859
00:46:42,591 --> 00:46:46,572
to keep teams that release average games.

860
00:46:47,172 --> 00:46:50,573
But it's also a moment where we can make things amazing.

861
00:46:50,633 --> 00:46:52,673
There's all sorts of games out there now

862
00:46:52,693 --> 00:46:54,754
on all sorts of different platforms.

863
00:46:55,394 --> 00:46:57,234
And a lot of the things that we all talk about and get

864
00:46:57,274 --> 00:46:59,215
celebrated in the awards ceremony last night

865
00:46:59,295 --> 00:47:00,655
are games that have personality.

866
00:47:01,355 --> 00:47:04,256
And their games celebrate the united creative direction

867
00:47:04,336 --> 00:47:05,277
of a studio.

868
00:47:05,317 --> 00:47:09,198
And I think that's truly the most rewarding work to do.

869
00:47:09,258 --> 00:47:11,099
So we should try to figure out how

870
00:47:11,139 --> 00:47:13,560
to help our studios towards that and be a part of that process.

871
00:47:14,800 --> 00:47:16,661
So remember those words.

872
00:47:17,421 --> 00:47:17,781
Thank you.

873
00:47:17,962 --> 00:47:18,262
That's it.

874
00:47:21,903 --> 00:47:22,103
OK?

875
00:47:24,444 --> 00:47:24,544
OK.

